WEBVTT

00:00:00.630 --> 00:00:14.590
PROFESSOR: The molecules and
Born-Oppenheimer approximation.

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:29.660
OK, we all know
that molecules are

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:34.370
a lot harder to
solve than atoms,

00:00:34.370 --> 00:00:37.790
and even atoms are
not that easy once you

00:00:37.790 --> 00:00:39.890
have more than one
electron because

00:00:39.890 --> 00:00:44.570
of the electrostatic
repulsion, but molecules

00:00:44.570 --> 00:00:51.110
are significantly different
in that one of the greatest

00:00:51.110 --> 00:00:54.200
simplicities that
we had with atoms

00:00:54.200 --> 00:01:00.230
is that the atom is such
that the potential created

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:04.280
by the nucleus is
spherically symmetric.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:10.440
When you have a molecule
you have separate nuclei

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:14.460
and therefore your
spherical symmetry is gone,

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:16.380
and whether you
have one electron

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:21.000
or more than one electron,
there is no spherical symmetry.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.450
All our tools of angular
momentum don't help us much.

00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:30.450
We have to start
the problem anew.

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:35.580
So the difficulty with
molecules is basically

00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:39.090
that the potential for the
electrons, where they move

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:43.450
is not spherically symmetric.

00:01:43.450 --> 00:01:45.220
There is another
thing that helps

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:49.690
us, however, is that there's a
nice separation of mass scales.

00:01:49.690 --> 00:01:53.410
You have the mass,
little m, of the electron

00:01:53.410 --> 00:01:58.660
and the nuclear mass, this
could be the mass of one nucleus

00:01:58.660 --> 00:02:02.570
or a mass of a few
nuclei or doesn't matter,

00:02:02.570 --> 00:02:10.460
but this is small, and typically
it is 10 to the minus 4.

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:13.850
You know, an electron is
about 2,000 times lighter

00:02:13.850 --> 00:02:15.260
than a single proton.

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:18.530
If you already have a nice
nucleus with a couple of them,

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:21.390
you're several
thousandths already there,

00:02:21.390 --> 00:02:24.150
so this is a nice number.

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:29.670
So we want to understand the
scales of the physics of this,

00:02:29.670 --> 00:02:31.710
so let's assume we
have a molecule,

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:39.310
maybe a has few centers and
then there's electronic cloud,

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:46.660
and it has a size
of the order of a.

00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:51.310
So we can estimate
at first sight what

00:02:51.310 --> 00:02:53.800
are the energies involved here?

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:56.980
What is the energy of the
electron, for example?

00:02:56.980 --> 00:03:00.400
And you can say the
momentum of the electron

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:06.055
is of the order of h bar
times the size of the cloud.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:17.300
It's an estimate, and the
energies, the electron

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:21.380
energies, are
basically determined

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:25.040
by the size in which
there are confined,

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:29.270
which is a, h bar, and
the mass of the electron.

00:03:29.270 --> 00:03:36.530
Those are the electronic
energy, so h squared over

00:03:36.530 --> 00:03:41.600
m a squared, those
are the right units,

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:47.030
is p squared over m, the units,
so it's natural like this.

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:56.400
So this is the
electronic configuration

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:59.280
and typical electronic
energy, so what

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:07.860
is the approximate picture
of the physics of a molecule?

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:16.260
Basically you have nuclei, and
the nuclei repel each other,

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:18.060
they want to be away.

00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:22.019
Now the electrons
come in and then they

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:29.410
fly around the nuclei, and the
electrons attract the nuclei

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:34.010
and attract the nuclei, so the
electrons, reasonably placed,

00:04:34.010 --> 00:04:37.240
compensate the
repulsion of the nuclei

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.810
by creating some new attraction.

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:45.640
At the end you get some
kind of equilibrium.

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:49.320
It's not classical because
you cannot create stable

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:51.750
equilibrium between
classical particles.

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:56.460
This is one of the amazing
things about quantum mechanics.

00:04:56.460 --> 00:04:59.220
You know very well
an atom would not

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:02.970
exist without quantum
mechanics, you

00:05:02.970 --> 00:05:06.930
would have stable classical
orbits, circular orbits,

00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:09.720
but they radiate
energy so they decay.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:15.180
If you have a molecule you
have two repelling positive

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:16.110
charged particles.

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:17.880
In [? E&M ?] you
saw the case when

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:20.130
you put the negative
charge in the middle

00:05:20.130 --> 00:05:24.420
and you create equilibrium,
but that's absolutely unstable.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:29.640
You move that electric charge
a micron and then off it goes,

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:31.980
the whole thing is unstable.

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:34.550
But quantum mechanics
solves those problems

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:41.730
and our physical picture is
that of repelling nuclei,

00:05:41.730 --> 00:05:44.970
an attracting cloud
of electrons creating

00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:50.340
an equilibrium in which
the nuclei are reasonably

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:53.970
well-localized, they're
quantum particles

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:56.490
but they're reasonably
well-localized,

00:05:56.490 --> 00:06:01.590
while the electrons are
completely delocalized.

00:06:01.590 --> 00:06:07.300
That is our picture, they
are moving in that way.

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:10.200
So our picture will
be-- we have that

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:17.220
and we have slow vibrations
of the nuclei that

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:20.230
are mostly localized.

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:27.260
And you can imagine calculating
the electronic configuration

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:31.460
for any particular
separation of the nuclei

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:33.800
and that's the cloud
for this separation.

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:39.020
As the nuclei vibrate, the
electronic configuration

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:43.780
probably adjusts
adiabatically to this thing

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:46.130
in the instantaneous
eigenstates,

00:06:46.130 --> 00:06:48.850
and they work that way.

00:06:48.850 --> 00:06:54.190
We're going to do that in
trying to understand things.

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:57.800
I also want to
emphasize this kind

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:02.690
of remarkable property
of an electron

00:07:02.690 --> 00:07:05.960
to create the bound state.

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:14.380
So we are not amazed on the
fact that if we have a proton

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:23.050
and we can have an electron
here, we create a bound state,

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:27.120
and that's a hydrogen atom.

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:37.860
But suppose I bring in
another proton from infinity.

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:42.340
Well, I-- if I
bring it, I'm going

00:07:42.340 --> 00:07:46.850
to start bringing it here,
this kind of is neutral

00:07:46.850 --> 00:07:51.510
but eventually this proton
is gonna polarize this thing.

00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:55.420
OK, I'm going to bring it
and then if I come too close

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:59.680
it repels it so it will
be a force repelling it

00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:02.200
and we have to figure
out what it does.

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:08.020
Suppose I try to bring it in.

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:15.960
Do you think that an electron
is capable of stabilizing

00:08:15.960 --> 00:08:17.940
two protons?

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:26.490
Can they create a cloud in which
an electron stabilizes the two

00:08:26.490 --> 00:08:27.180
protons?

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:29.870
Is that possible
or not possible?

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:34.870
There's a lot of protons
for one single electron.

00:08:34.870 --> 00:08:36.900
Is that possible or not?

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:41.575
All right, you say yes,
yes, any other opinions?

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:46.930
Can that happen?

00:08:46.930 --> 00:08:51.992
Can the electric produce a bound
state of two protons like that?

00:08:51.992 --> 00:08:53.450
AUDIENCE: Isn't
that just hydrogen?

00:08:53.450 --> 00:08:54.158
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:08:54.158 --> 00:08:56.204
AUDIENCE: Isn't
that just hydrogen?

00:08:56.204 --> 00:08:57.120
PROFESSOR: It is what?

00:08:57.120 --> 00:08:58.614
AUDIENCE: Isn't
that just hydrogen?

00:08:58.614 --> 00:09:01.610
Or [INAUDIBLE]
hydrogen [INAUDIBLE]??

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:04.510
PROFESSOR: OK, yes,
it can produce it,

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:10.210
and this would be called,
with an electron here,

00:09:10.210 --> 00:09:14.098
the hydrogen
molecule ion, so H2+.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:21.220
It's a hydrogen molecule
that had these two things

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:26.410
and it lost one electron,
and yes, this can be done

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:29.500
and we'll analyze it.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:33.490
And now you can
get greedy and say,

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:37.950
can you get an electron to
stabilize three protons?

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:41.740
Yes or no?

